Introduction¶

In this report we try to answer a series of questions on how we could reduce CO$^{2}$ emissions by making changes to how we commute around Ireland.

We collected data, cleaned it, then conducted a series of exploration and visualisation of our data. We identified a particular subset of our data to drill down into so we could extract details to explain current habits causing CO$^{2}$ emissions and what we could do to lower them.

This report first defines the problem we are trying to tackle. It then gives a brief overview of each dataset and where they were collected from. We then go through an iterative process of cleaning and selecting features to create a workable dataset. Once we have a cleaned dataset this report provides visuals of our data to analyse. At the bottom of each graph we try make some observations on the data to help us identify a particular subset of our data to further examine. With a particular subset we then try to answer questions and return a list of recommendations which could help reduce CO$^{2}$ emissions.

Problem definition¶

The european protection agency, 2021 stated that "human activities are estimated to have caused approximately 1.0°C of global warming above pre-industrial levels with a likely range of 0.8°C to 1.2°C". The EPA believes we are on course to exceed the paris climate agreement of remaining between 1.5°C to 2°C above pre-industrial levels. This will impact ireland from a decrease in frequency of summer rain fall and an increase in of heavy winter rain, it will change wind strength and put stress on crops. Rising sea levels will cause coastal erosion, flooding and damage to both infastructure or propery in all major cities in Ireland that are located near the coast.This would affect the Irish economy, human health and wellbeing.

According to the Sustainability Energy Authority of Ireland (SEAI), 2021) transportation accounts for 40% of our kilo tonne of C02 put into the atmosphere.

Reducing the number of petrol and diesel vehicles on Irish roads could reduce this 40% figure. Ways to reduce the number of vehicles on the road are for commuters to change to electric vehicles, cycle more or use public transport.

This report will look at

  • Different modes of transport for people in ireland
  • Understanding from the data what makes people choose personal transport over public transport.
  • Investigate, from the data, how to increase public transport usage.

The following data visualisation was inspired on data analysis related to Chicago Transit data such as work by (Reid, 2018)

About Dataset¶

The following 10 data sets are based on mobility in Ireland and were taken from the Central Statistics Office (CSO) on Commuting in Ireland via their interactive API portal. The data was collected from various census surveys conducted in Ireland. Each data set is stored in a folder called /data/.

  • E6010_mobility_by_past30yrs

  • E6038_people_at_work

  • E6043_mobility_by_class

  • E6006_travel_duration

  • E6013_mobility_by_geo

  • E6040_travel_time_by_age

  • E6016.mobility_by_students

  • E6034.people_working_in_towns_suburbs

  • E6018.mobility_by_students_from_towns

  • E6023.mobility_by_students_from_geo

*further descriptions about columns can be found here

def format_columns(data_frame):
    formated_names = {}
    for col_name in data_frame.columns:
        name = col_name.lower() # could also have used df = df.rename(str.lower, axis='columns')
        name = name.replace(' ', '_')
        formated_names[col_name] = name
    return data_frame.rename(columns=formated_names)

def categorise_objects(data_frame):
    for col_name in data_frame.columns:
        dt = data_frame.dtypes[col_name]
        if dt == object:
            data_frame[col_name] = data_frame[col_name].astype('category')
    return data_frame

Dataset 1: mobility_by_past30yrs dataset description¶

The following is a brief description of each feature in this dataset.

  1. Statistic column only has 1 value which is not useful to us. We will remove this.
  2. Census Year is important it is a date range for 7 different census surveys taken over 30 years
  3. Sex
  • has 3 options one is called 'Both Sexes'
  • 'Both Sexes'was renamed to all via df = df.replace({'Both sexes': 'all'})
  • when viewing dataset it appears to be a summation of other columns.
  • any 'all' in dataset will be removed.
  1. Means of Travel
  • has 'not stated and 'all means of travel'
  • 'all means of travel' was renamed to all via df = df.replace({'Both sexes': 'all'})
  • any 'all' in dataset will be removed.
  • motor car has both a driver and a passenger option
  • some names could be changed for brevity, e.g
    • All means of travel -> all
    • Work mainly at or from home -> remote work
    • On foot -> walking
    • bicycle -> bike
    • Bus, minibus or coach -> bus
    • Motorcycle or scooter -> motorbike
    • Motor car: Driver -> car
    • Motor car: Passenger -> carpool
    • Other means (incl. lorry or van) - truck
  1. At Work School or College
  • this column shows the level of education a person has
  • but it also contains age data
  • we could seperate these two into a new column age and edu_level
  • this seperation would be based on info available from citizens information
  • we can also make use of retirement age of 66 for range https://www.citizensinformation.ie/en/employment/retirement/older_people_and_working/retirement_age_in_ireland.html
  • Although the oldest person to graduate in ireland was 82 after starting university in 2017 at 79, we will assume those stated in university are aged between 19 to 66 https://www.independent.ie/regionals/newrossstandard/irelands-oldest-student-tom-thrilled-to-collect-degree-38638703.html
  • 'all persons' could be removed or held as a seperate database
  • 'all persons' isn't describe clearly. e.g Is the person has no education or is 89 years old?
    • some names could be changed for brevity as well, e.g
      • 'All persons',
      • 'Children at school aged between 5 and 12 years', 5-12 | primary-school
      • 'Population aged 15 years and over at work', >=15 | junior-cert
      • 'Students at school or college aged between 13 and 18 years', 13-18 | leaving-cert
      • 'Students at school or college aged 19 years a...', 19-up | university
  1. Unit
  • supposed to be if the unit of measure is km, mins, etc but for this dataset it is just number
  • since one number we will remove
  1. Value
  • is number of people we will keep

Further data cleaning, and feature engineering¶

In [11]:
#we can now format columns (e.g drop a column or seperate a column)
df = df.drop('statistic', axis=1) # axis 0 will drop label, 1 will drop column
df = df.rename(columns={'censusyear':'year'})#we can drop census from name of column
df = df.replace({'Both sexes': 'all'}) #we rename 'Both sexes' values to 'all'
#rename means of travel
df['means_of_travel'] = df['means_of_travel'].cat.rename_categories({
    'On foot': 'walking', 
    'Bicycle': 'bike', 
    'Bus, minibus or coach': 'bus', 
    'Train, DART or LUAS': 'train', 
    'Motorcycle or scooter': 'motorbike',
    'Motor car: Driver': 'car',
    'Motor car: Passenger': 'carpool',
    'Other means (incl. lorry or van)': 'truck',
    'Work mainly at or from home' : 'remote',
    'All means of travel' : 'all',
    'Not stated' : 'na'
})

#split out at_work_school_or_college
age_range = []
edu_status = []
for value in df['at_work_school_or_college']:
    if value == "All persons":
        age_range.append("all")
        edu_status.append("all")
    elif value == "Children at school aged between 5 and 12 years":
        age_range.append("5-12")
        edu_status.append("at primary school")
    elif value == "Population aged 15 years and over at work":
        age_range.append("15-66")
        edu_status.append("working")
    elif value == "Students at school or college aged between 13 and 18 years":
        age_range.append("13-18")
        edu_status.append("at secondary school")
    elif value == "Students at school or college aged 19 years and over":
        age_range.append("19-66")
        edu_status.append("at university")  
df['age_range'] = age_range
df['edu_status'] = edu_status

#we now don't need this column anymore
df = df.drop('at_work_school_or_college', axis=1)

#we can drop units
df = df.drop('unit', axis=1)

#now we remove every 'all' row
df = df[df.sex != 'all']
df = df[df.means_of_travel != 'all']
df = df[df.age_range != 'all']
df = df[df.edu_status != 'all']

#rearange columns so value is at end
df = df[['year', 'sex', 'means_of_travel', 'age_range', 'edu_status', 'value']]

def skewness_kurtosis(data_frame):
    #ref https://medium.com/@atanudan/kurtosis-skew-function-in-pandas-aa63d72e20de
    skew = data_frame['value'].skew(axis=0)
    #data skewness - helps us determine what models are suitable (e.g regession models like normal distribution)
    print("Skew: ")
    print(skew)
    if(-0.5 > skew < 0.5):
        print("data is fairly symmetrical\n")
    elif(-1.0 > skew < -0.5 or 0.5 > skew <1.0):
        print("data is moderately skewed\n")
    elif(-1.0 < skew > 1.0):
        print("data is highly skewed\n")
        
    #data kurtosis - used to find outliers
    kurt = data_frame['value'].kurt(axis=0)
    print("Kurtosis: ")
    print(kurt)
    if(3.0 < kurt):
        print("data has a leptokurtic distribution(tall+thin)\n")
    elif( 3.0 > kurt):
        print("data has a platykurtic distribution(Moderately Spread Out)\n")
    elif(kurt == 3.0):
        print("data has a mesokurtic distribution(similar to normal distribution)\n")

skewness_kurtosis(df_test)

Cleaning Dataset 3 : df_mobility_by_class¶

In [35]:
#we pick a dataset to look at and we clean it
df = df_mobility_by_class
#get header names but keep column order
list(df.columns.values)
#loop through columns, remove white spaces
#this is to help accessing values later
df = format_columns(df)#our custom function for formatting dataframes
#loop through columns if data type is object convert it to category
df = categorise_objects(df)#our custom function for categorising dataframes
list_unique_cats(df)#our custom function for viewing each category value
#we can now format columns (e.g drop a column or seperate a column)

#descriptions of dataset
    #social_class - what level of skill and pay someone gets for their profession
#clean dataset
df = df.drop('statistic', axis=1) # axis 0 will drop label, 1 will drop column
df = df.rename(columns={'censusyear':'year'})#we can drop census from name of column
df = df.replace({'All social classes': 'all'}) #we rename 'Both sexes' values to 'all'
#rename means of travel
df['social_class'] = df['social_class'].cat.rename_categories({
    'Professional workers': 'self-employed', 
    'Managerial and technical': 'employed-managerial', 
    'Non-manual': 'employed-admin-workers', 
    'Skilled manual': 'trade-workers',
    'Semi-skilled': 'manual-workers',
    'All other gainfully occupied and unknown': 'unemployed',
    
})

#rename means of travel
df['means_of_travel'] = df['means_of_travel'].cat.rename_categories({
    'On foot': 'walking', 
    'Bicycle': 'bike', 
    'Bus, minibus or coach': 'bus', 
    'Train, DART or LUAS': 'train', 
    'Motorcycle or scooter': 'motorbike',
    'Motor car: Driver': 'car',
    'Motor car: Passenger': 'carpool',
    'Other, incl. lorry': 'truck', #we remove brackets to detect this value
    'Work mainly at or from home' : 'remote',
    'All means of travel' : 'all',
    'Not stated' : 'na'
})

#we need to combine van to truck
df = df.replace({'Van': 'truck'}) #we rename 'Both sexes' values to 'all'
#we can drop unit like before
df = df.drop('unit', axis=1)

#now we remove every 'all' rows and n/a rows
df = df[df.social_class != 'all']
df = df[df.means_of_travel != 'all']
df = df[df.means_of_travel != 'na']

#now we save our clean dataset to use later for visualisation                                                                                                              
df.to_csv(r'./data/E6043_mobility_by_class_cleaned.csv', index=False) #we don't want an auto index
#test we saved successfully
df_test = pd.read_csv (r'./data/E6043_mobility_by_class_cleaned.csv')

#split out at_work_school_or_college
age_range = []
edu_status = []
for value in df['at_work_school_or_college']:
    if value == "All persons":
        age_range.append("all")
        edu_status.append("all")
    elif value == "Children at school aged between 5 and 12 years":
        age_range.append("5-12")
        edu_status.append("at primary school")
    elif value == "Population aged 15 years and over at work":
        age_range.append("15-66")
        edu_status.append("working")
    elif value == "Students at school or college aged between 13 and 18 years":
        age_range.append("13-18")
        edu_status.append("at secondary school")
    elif value == "Students at school or college aged 19 years and over":
        age_range.append("19-66")
        edu_status.append("at university")  
df['age_range'] = age_range
df['edu_status'] = edu_status

We can change ordinal variable travelling_time to numeric in pandas by averaging the text as per below:

  • '< ¼ hour': 0.125,
  • '¼ hour - < ½ hour': 0.275,
  • '½ hour - < ¾ hour': 0.375,
  • '¾ hour - < 1 hour': 0.525,
  • '1 hour - < 1½ hours': 1.25,
  • '1½ hours and over': 1.30,

    #statistic - has more than one but towns_with_a_population_of_over_1,500 gives same details so will drop
#clean dataset

df = df.replace({'Not stated': 'na'}) #we rename any missing rows


#rename means of travel
df['means_of_travel'] = df['means_of_travel'].cat.rename_categories({
    'On foot': 'walking', 
    'Bicycle': 'bike', 
    'Bus, minibus or coach': 'bus', 
    'Train, DART or LUAS': 'train', 
    'Motorcycle or scooter': 'motorbike',
    'Motor car: Driver': 'car',
    'Motor car: Passenger': 'carpool',
    'Other, incl. lorry': 'truck', #we remove brackets to detect this value
    'Work mainly at or from home' : 'remote',
    'All means of travel' : 'all',
    'Not stated' : 'na'
})

#we need to combine van to truck
df = df.replace({'Van': 'truck'}) #we rename 'Both sexes' values to 'all'

#rename long column name
df = df.rename(columns={'aggregate_town_size': 'town_size'})

#split out at_work_school_or_college
age_range = []
edu_status = []
for value in df['at_work_school_or_college']:
    if value == "All persons":
        age_range.append("all")
        edu_status.append("all")
    elif value == "Children at school aged between 5 and 12 years":
        age_range.append("5-12")
        edu_status.append("at primary school")
    elif value == "Population aged 15 years and over at work":
        age_range.append("15-66")
        edu_status.append("working")
    elif value == "Students at school or college aged between 13 and 18 years":
        age_range.append("13-18")
        edu_status.append("at secondary school")
    elif value == "Students at school or college aged 19 years and over":
        age_range.append("19-66")
        edu_status.append("at university")  
df['age_range'] = age_range
df['edu_status'] = edu_status

df = df[df.means_of_travel != 'all']

def desc_stats(df):
    mean = df['value'].mean()
    median = df['value'].median()
    mode = df['value'].mode()
    std = df['value'].std()
    cov = std / mean
    print ("mean: " + str(mean) + ",\nmedian: " + str(median) + ",\nstd dev: " + str(std) + ",\ncoefficient of variation: " + str(cov) +"\n")

  • Over the years we have had to increasingly rely on cars for mobility both as drivers or through carpooling. We have also seen more trucks on the road.
  • Although it has decreased slightly we still walk everywhere if we are not driving.
  • Our cycling use has decreased and so has our bus use. There was no real change in motorbike use.
  • Remote work in this case includes those working on their own farms and those who were homemakers. More woman in the workplace and those leaving farms to take up work in the city could help explain why working remotely has decreased. Cenus data are taken every 5 years. This data is before covid so in a future dataset we may see this sharply increase.

fig_3, ax_3 = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 36), nrows=7) # we create a subplot

# Add some text for labels, title and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.
year = 1986
width = 0.45  # the width of the bars

for i in range(7):
    year = year if i==0 else year + 5
    
    #We create a table of males and females indexed by means of travel
    who_travels = mdf_30[i].pivot_table(index='means_of_travel', columns='sex', values='value')
    x = np.arange(len(who_travels.index))  # the label locations
    
    males = ax_3[i].bar(x - width/2, who_travels.Male, width, label='Men')
    females = ax_3[i].bar(x + width/2, who_travels.Female, width, label='Women')
    ax_3[i].set_ylabel('Commuters [#]')
    
    ax_3[i].set_title('How we got around in ' + str(year))
    ax_3[i].set_xticks(x)
    ax_3[i].set_xticklabels(who_travels.index)
    ax_3[i].legend()
    ax_3[i].bar_label(males, padding=3)
    ax_3[i].bar_label(females, padding=3)


fig_3.tight_layout()
plt.show()

    ax_4[i].bar(x-width, who_travels.truck,width, label='Truck', bottom=who_travels.walking);
    ax_4[i].bar(x-width, who_travels.walking,width, label='Walking');
    
    ax_4[i].legend();

fig_4.tight_layout()
plt.show()

How females got around¶

  • From the stacked bar charts we can see that females originally walked more or used public transport, they hardly drove.
  • As the years passed they used cars more and walking less. It could be due to females leaving the home and working in towns.
  • Interestingly we see carpooling more amoung females increase and with public transport decrease. It could be explained by safety related issues.

How males got around¶

  • similarly to females we see public transport used less over the years.
  • Car usage increase while walking decreased. It could be due to males getting work in towns instead of on farms.
  • Truck usage amoung males also increased, this includes vans. Here, we assume it is also work related.

Summary Conclusion of Data Exploration¶

What the data shows¶

  • Commuters rely heavily on personal transportation or commercial vehicles (e.g vans) to earn a living in Ireland.
  • Commuters are working less at home or on the farm.
  • Commuters of ireland are walking and cycling less.
  • Commuters transport via buses is declining and commuters hardly anyone is using trains
  • Commuters are driving their kids to school well into leaving cert in secondary school. We see this with an increase of carpooling amoung females and a decrease of public transport.
  • The use of cars as personal transport starts to increase as young adults in university and progresses to working life.
  • Most Commuters who work are employees of a company while self employement is dominated by males
  • Car usage is dominated by trade workers, manual workers and employees of companies.
  • Most commuting live in towns fo 1,500 Commuters or more, in Dublin City, Cork city, Limerick city, galway city and waterford city
  • Public transport is not used from towns as much and there is not a heavy use of trains.
  • We see walking is high in towns.
  • The rest of the country outside of large towns and cities requires either their own car or to carpool with someone.
  • Commuters in Dublin City, Meath, Fingal, South Dubin, County Cork, Kildare and Wicklow experience commuting over an hour more than the rest of the country

Assumptions made from data¶

  • More women entered the work force from 1986 and more families left farming to take up work in towns and cities.
  • Comuters live futher away from towns and cities due to house prices so are unable to walk or have access to public transport.
  • Quality of public transport in terms of duration to reach destination and safety of journey decreased so commuters were less likely to use it. No subways exist and no proper investment in train networks was made.
  • Quality of national roads, regional roads and those in towns or cities was poor and increased traffic congestion which decreased road safety. This could be why we see a decline in cycling and little motorbike use.
  • Majority of male self employeed workers are tradesmen commuting to and from work sites.

Question 1 - Which commuters emmit CO$^{2}$ and which do not?¶

Using the (European Parlement, 2019) breakdown of vehicle emmissions we can sub divide our dataset into emmiters and non emmiters. Vehicle emmissions are listed as follows:

Vehicle % CO$^{2}$
Cars 60.7%
Trucks 26.2%
Bus 11.9%
Motorcycles 1.2%
Trains 0.5%

This suggests that the following do not emit CO$^{2}$, in terms of transportation:

  • Remote Working (Includes Homemaking)
  • Walking
  • Using a Bicycle

We will break the dataset up into two groups and drill down into each attribute.

Question 2 - What is the relationship between commuters emmit CO$^{2}$ and means of travel?¶

Chi-Square Test¶

We perform a chi-squred test to see if there is a statistically significant difference sex and means of travel for both emitters and non CO$^{2}$ emitters. We test to see if there is a significant relationship between two nominal variables by comparing their frequencies.

In [ ]:
contigency = pd.crosstab(df_e.sex, df_e.means_of_travel, df_e.commuters, aggfunc="sum", rownames=["sex"], colnames=[None])
#contigency.head()
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8)) 
sns.heatmap(contigency, annot=True, cmap="YlGnBu")
# Chi-square test of independence. 
stat1, p1, dof1, expected1 = chi2_contingency(contigency)

Inference Sex vs Means of Travel¶

In [ ]:
alpha = 0.05

print('Significance=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (alpha, p1))
if p1 <= alpha:
    print('-> Variables are associated')
else:
    print('-> Variables are not associated')
    
# Print the p-value
print(p1)

The null hypothesis was that means of travel and sex are independent.The p-value is less than 0.01% which means that we do not reject the null hypothesis at 95% level of confidence.

Conclusion & Recommendations¶

Transportation accounts for 40% of Ireland's kilo tonne of CO$^{2}$ it puts into the atmosphere. This is affecting the climate and creating a green house gas effect which is raising global temperatures. This report asked how we could reduce CO$^{2}$ emissions by making changes to how we commute around Ireland.

We found out the following through data exploration:

  • Commuters rely heavily on personal transportation or commercial vehicles (e.g vans) to earn a living in Ireland.
  • Commuters are working less at home or on the farm.
  • Commuters of ireland are walking and cycling less.
  • Commuters transport via buses is declining and commuters hardly anyone is using trains
  • Commuters are driving their kids to school well into leaving cert in secondary school. We see this with an increase of carpooling amoung females and a decrease of public transport.
  • The use of cars as personal transport starts to increase as young adults in university and progresses to working life.
  • Most Commuters who work are employees of a company while self employement is dominated by males
  • Car usage is dominated by trade workers, manual workers and employees of companies.
  • Most commuting live in towns fo 1,500 Commuters or more, in Dublin City, Cork city, Limerick city, galway city and waterford city
  • Public transport is not used from towns as much and there is not a heavy use of trains.
  • We see walking is high in towns.
  • The rest of the country outside of large towns and cities requires either their own car or to carpool with someone.
  • Commuters in Dublin City, Meath, Fingal, South Dubin, County Cork, Kildare and Wicklow experience commuting over an hour more than the rest of the country

We made the following assumptions on our findings:

  • More women entered the work force from 1986 and more families left farming to take up work in towns and cities.
  • Comuters live futher away from towns and cities due to house prices so are unable to walk or have access to public transport.
  • Quality of public transport in terms of duration to reach destination and safety of journey decreased so commuters were less likely to use it. No subways exist and no proper investment in train networks was made.
  • Quality of national roads, regional roads and those in towns or cities was poor and increased traffic congestion which decreased road safety. This could be why we see a decline in cycling and little motorbike use.
  • Majority of male self employeed workers are tradesmen commuting to and from work sites.

We asked which commuters are emmitting CO$^{2}$ and found that 79.31% of commuters emmit CO$^{2}$ and 20.69% do not. For us to reduce CO$^{2}$ emissions we would have to enable and encourage the 79% to transition to non poluting means of transport.

We asked What was the relationship between commuters emmit CO$^{2}$ and means of travel. We found from our Chi-Square test that Sex, age and education status are all interdependent on means of travel. We saw men are more likely to emit more polution by means of driving heavy poluting vehicles while women more likely to avail of public transport or carpooling. Working class adults and children made up a lot of car usage.

This report recommends to reduce 20% of car usage by implementing the following:

  • Invest in more train and subway access to increase walking among commuters.
  • Allow working from home where possible amoung working class men.
  • Invest in more bus networks to local schools and offer next ride free for parents to encourage them to take the bus to work.
  • Improve quality of roads and security on bus networks to decrease the amount of carpooling amoung female commuters.
  • Construct cycling lanes in all major towns and cities seperate from bus lanes.
  • offer income tax reduction incentives to drivers of carpools and offer employee meal tax subsidies to businesses that promote carpooling or remote working among employees.
  • Review latest cenus when complete to determine how many electric cars are used by commuters.
  • Include more numeric data to complement CSO's categorical data.
